ourish in that country. Providing an historical overview of Buddhist women in China and Taiwan, DeVido discusses various reasons for the vibrancy of Taiwan's nuns' orders. She introduces us to the nuns of the best-known of order, the Buddhist Compassion-Relief Foundation (Ciji) as well as those of the Luminary Buddhist Institute. Discussing "Buddhism for the Human Realm," DeVido asks whether this popular philosophy has encouraged and supported the singular strength of Taiwan's Buddhism women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhist nunszTaiwan. 0aWomen in BuddhismzTaiwan. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438431499?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438431499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438431499/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles